---
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import { SITE_TITLE, SITE_DESCRIPTION } from '../consts';
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
	<head>
		<BaseHead title={SITE_TITLE} description={SITE_DESCRIPTION} />
		<script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
			"@context": "https://schema.org",
			"@type": "Article",
			"headline": "What Happens If You Get a DUI in California?",
			"description": "A plain-English breakdown of the court process, DMV deadlines, penalties, and long-term consequences of a California DUI arrest.",
			"url": "https://caliduihelp.com/",
			"publisher": {
				"@type": "Organization",
				"name": "CaliDUIHelp",
				"url": "https://caliduihelp.com"
			},
			"datePublished": "2026-04-19",
			"dateModified": "2026-04-19"
		})} />
		<style>
			main {
				width: 720px;
				max-width: calc(100% - 2em);
				margin: auto;
				padding: 3em 1em;
			}
			.disclaimer {
				background: #fff8e1;
				border-left: 4px solid #f59e0b;
				padding: 0.75em 1em;
				border-radius: 4px;
				font-size: 0.9em;
				color: #7c6400;
				margin-bottom: 2em;
			}
			h1 {
				font-size: 1.6em;
				margin-bottom: 0.3em;
			}
			h2 {
				font-size: 1.15em;
				margin-top: 2em;
				margin-bottom: 0.5em;
			}
			h3 {
				font-size: 1em;
				margin-top: 1.5em;
				margin-bottom: 0.3em;
			}
			.subtitle {
				color: rgb(var(--gray));
				margin-bottom: 2em;
				font-size: 1em;
			}
			table {
				width: 100%;
				border-collapse: collapse;
				margin: 1em 0;
			}
			th, td {
				text-align: left;
				padding: 0.6em 0.8em;
				border: 1px solid rgb(var(--gray-light));
			}
			th {
				background: rgb(var(--gray-light));
			}
			.callout {
				background: #f0f4ff;
				border-left: 4px solid #2337ff;
				padding: 0.75em 1em;
				border-radius: 4px;
				margin: 1.5em 0;
			}
			.callout.warning {
				background: #fff0f0;
				border-left-color: #dc2626;
			}
			.callout.green {
				background: #f0fdf4;
				border-left-color: #16a34a;
			}
			ol li, ul li {
				margin-bottom: 0.4em;
			}
		</style>
	</head>
	<body>
		<Header />
		<main>
			<div class="disclaimer">
				<strong>Not legal advice.</strong> This site provides general information only. If you've been arrested for DUI, consult a licensed California attorney.
			</div>

			<h1>What Happens If You Get a DUI in California?</h1>
			<p class="subtitle">Last updated: April 2026</p>

			<p>When someone gets pulled over and arrested for DUI, two separate things start at the same time: a criminal case in court, and a DMV case about your license. These are completely independent — you can actually win one and lose the other.</p>

			<hr />

			<h2>The Court Process (Step by Step)</h2>
			<ol>
				<li><strong>Arrest &amp; booking</strong> — You might get held for a few hours or overnight.</li>
				<li><strong>Arraignment</strong> — Your first court appearance. You enter a plea: guilty, not guilty, or no contest.</li>
				<li><strong>Pre-trial / negotiation</strong> — This is where a lawyer might try to reduce the charge (like to a "wet reckless").</li>
				<li><strong>Trial</strong> — Most cases don't make it here. They usually get resolved before this.</li>
			</ol>

			<hr />

			<h2>The DMV Side (This Catches People Off Guard)</h2>
			<p>After a DUI arrest, you typically have <strong>10 days to request a DMV hearing</strong>. If you don't:</p>
			<div class="callout warning">
				Your license automatically gets suspended — even if you haven't gone to court yet.
			</div>
			<p>The DMV case moves completely independently from your criminal case. Don't ignore it.</p>

			<hr />

			<h2>What the Penalties Actually Feel Like</h2>

			<h3>Jail Time</h3>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>First offense:</strong> usually little to none — often probation instead</li>
				<li><strong>Second/third offense:</strong> way more likely to serve actual time</li>
			</ul>

			<h3>Fines</h3>
			<ul>
				<li>Base fine might be ~$390, but after court fees and assessments it's easily <strong>$2,000–$10,000 total</strong></li>
			</ul>

			<h3>License Suspension</h3>
			<ul>
				<li>First offense: ~4–6 months (sometimes you can drive with restrictions)</li>
			</ul>

			<h3>DUI School</h3>
			<ul>
				<li>First offense: 3–9 months</li>
				<li>Repeat offenders: up to 18–30 months</li>

			</ul>

			<h3>Ignition Interlock Device (IID)</h3>
			<ul>
				<li>You blow into it before your car will start</li>
				<li>Becoming more common even for first offenses</li>
			</ul>

			<h3>Probation</h3>
			<p>Usually 3–5 years, with conditions like:</p>
			<ul>
				<li>No driving with any alcohol in your system</li>
				<li>Don't refuse chemical tests again</li>
				<li>No new offenses</li>
			</ul>

			<hr />

			<h2>"Wet Reckless" — This Can Make a Big Difference</h2>
			<p>A <strong>wet reckless</strong> (California Vehicle Code 23103.5) is a reduced charge that a lawyer might be able to negotiate for a first-time case. Compared to a DUI conviction:</p>
			<div class="callout green">
				<ul style="margin:0; padding-left:1.2em;">
					<li>Lesser charge on your record</li>
					<li>Lower fines</li>
					<li>Shorter DUI school program</li>
					<li>Less overall impact</li>
				</ul>
			</div>
			<p>The catch: it still counts as a prior DUI if you get another one later.</p>

			<hr />

			<h2>Things That Make It Worse (Even if Still a Misdemeanor)</h2>
			<p>Penalties can increase even without an injury if:</p>
			<ul>
				<li>Your BAC was <strong>0.15% or higher</strong></li>
				<li>You were speeding or driving recklessly</li>
				<li>You <strong>refused a breath/blood test</strong></li>
				<li>There was a child in the car</li>
			</ul>

			<hr />

			<h2>Long-Term Consequences People Underestimate</h2>
			<ul>
				<li>Car insurance can skyrocket</li>
				<li>Shows up on background checks</li>
				<li>Can affect jobs — especially driving jobs</li>
				<li>Stays on your driving record for <strong>10 years</strong></li>
			</ul>
		</main>
		<Footer />
	</body>
</html>
